{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BgyGytUd79JrLbLZbPeM4r","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all the information needed. Let me compile a comprehensive report on how the Cloche DSL parser works and how step configs like \"prompt\" and \"script\" paths are stored.\n\n## DSL Parser Analysis Report\n\nBased on my review of the Cloche codebase, here's a comprehensive understanding of how the DSL parser works and how step configs are stored:\n\n### 1. DSL Parser Architecture\n\nThe DSL parser is located in `/workspace/internal/dsl/` and consists of:\n\n**Files:**\n- `/workspace/internal/dsl/parser.go` - Main parser implementation\n- `/workspace/internal/dsl/lexer.go` - Tokenizer/lexer\n- `/workspace/internal/dsl/token.go` - Token type definitions\n- `/workspace/internal/dsl/parser_test.go` - Comprehensive test suite\n\n### 2. How Step Configs Are Stored\n\nWhen a step is parsed, its configuration fields (including \"prompt\" and \"script\" paths) are stored as **raw strings** in a `map[string]string` called `Config`:\n\n```go\n// From parser.go, lines 151-154\nstep := &domain.Step{\n    Name:   nameTok.Literal,\n    Config: make(map[string]string),\n}\n```\n\n### 3. How \"prompt\" and \"script\" Paths Are Handled\n\nThe parser stores path values exactly as they appear in the DSL file:\n\n**For `prompt` fields:**\n- Syntax: `prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")`\n- Stored value: `file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")` (the complete function call string, lines 310-326)\n- Parser recognizes `file(...)` as a function call and preserves it verbatim\n\n**For `script` or `run` fields:**\n- Syntax: `run = \"go test ./... 2>&1\"`\n- Stored value: `go test ./... 2>&1` (the plain string, lines 298-302)\n- Simple strings are stored without quotes\n\n**For `script` fields (literal paths):**\n- Syntax: `script = \".cloche/scripts/build.sh\"`\n- Stored value: `.cloche/scripts/build.sh` (the plain string)\n\n### 4. Path Resolution\n\nThe actual file path resolution happens **later**, not during parsing. Examples:\n\n**In handler.go (lines 1174-1199):** The `handleAPIStepContent` function reads the actual content:\n```go\nif prompt := step.Config[\"prompt\"]; prompt != \"\" {\n    data, err := os.ReadFile(filepath.Join(dir, prompt))\n    // Returns error if prompt contains \"file(...)\" instead of extracting path\n}\n```\n\n**Important:** The handler code attempts to read paths directly without parsing the `file(...)` wrapper, suggesting either:\n1. The paths should be stored without the `file()` wrapper, OR\n2. There's post-processing of the config values elsewhere\n\n### 5. Test Evidence\n\nFrom `/workspace/internal/dsl/parser_test.go`:\n\n**Line 42:** Shows that `file(\"prompts/implement.md\")` is stored as-is:\n```go\nassert.Equal(t, `file(\"prompts/implement.md\")`, code.Config[\"prompt\"])\n```\n\n**Lines 53-68:** Minimal workflow test shows `run` commands are stored as plain strings:\n```go\nassert.Equal(t, \"make test && make lint\", check.Config[\"run\"])\n```\n\n### 6. Step Type Inference\n\nSteps are automatically typed based on which config field is present (lines 166-195):\n- **StepTypeAgent**: has \"prompt\" field\n- **StepTypeScript**: has \"run\" field  \n- **StepTypeWorkflow**: has \"workflow_name\" field\n\nA step can have exactly ONE of these; having multiple or none causes a parse error.\n\n### 7. Container Configuration\n\nSub-blocks are supported and stored with dot notation (lines 211-220):\n```go\ncontainer {\n    image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\", \"internal.example.com\"]\n}\n```\n\nStored as:\n- `container.image` → `cloche/agent:latest`\n- `container.network_allow` → `docs.python.org,internal.example.com` (comma-separated)\n\n### 8. Sample Workflow Format\n\nFrom `/workspace/.cloche/develop.cloche`:\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"go test ./... 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail -> abort\n}\n```\n\n### 9. Web Handler Integration\n\nIn `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/handler.go`, the API endpoint `handleAPIStepContent` (lines 1134-1199) uses the stored config values to resolve actual file paths. The handler assumes prompt values are **relative to the project directory** (`filepath.Join(dir, prompt)`).\n\nThis mismatch with `file(\"...\")` syntax suggests the DSL parser should extract the path from within the function call, or the handler should parse it.\n\n## Summary\n\n- **Storage location**: `Step.Config[\"fieldname\"]` (map of strings)\n- **Prompt paths**: Stored as complete `file(\"path\")` function calls\n- **Script/run commands**: Stored as plain command strings\n- **Resolution**: Happens at runtime in handlers, using relative paths from project root\n- **Key files**: Parser at `/workspace/internal/dsl/parser.go`, handlers at `/workspace/internal/adapters/web/handler.go`"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a832f9ab25fdd6c42 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 59435\ntool_uses: 16\nduration_ms: 22590</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"503a9c6b-ea73-4496-a067-8391d86da200","uuid":"da63295e-cfe4-4f98-a910-87068404fd23","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"I need to understand how the Cloche DSL parser works, specifically how step configs like \"prompt\" and \"script\" paths are stored. Find and read:\n\n1. The DSL parser (likely in internal/ somewhere, look for dsl package)\n2. Any test files for the handler, especially tests for handleAPIStepContent\n3. Any test files for the web handler\n4. A sample .cloche workflow file to see what format the paths are in\n\nRead the full contents of these files.","agentId":"a832f9ab25fdd6c42","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have all t